# PAGE 5

Panel 1
[GROUP] opens up a shared row of panels. Panels after it will join into its row. 

The next layout tag such as [H] for Horizontal or [V] for Vertical  will close the group

    +-------------+
    |.....P1......|
    +---+-----+---+
    |.P2|..P3.|.P4|
    +---+-----+---+
    |.....P5......|
    +-------------+

Panel 2 [GROUP]
Panel 3
Panel 4
Panel 5 [H]

# PAGE 6

Panel 1 [V][L]
Shapes can be mixed on a single panel, In a MANGA a [V]+[L] will create a Tall Rectangle, P2/P3 stack to its left.

P4 takes a full-width row.

    +------+------+
    |..P2..|......|
    +------+..P1..+
    |..P3..|......|
    +------+------+
    |.....P4......|
    +---+-----+---+
    |.P6...|.. .P5|
    +---+-----+---+

Panel 2
Panel 3
Panel 4 [H]
Panel 5 [GROUP]
Panel 6

# PAGE 7

Panel 1 [V][L]
[G] is an alias for [GROUP] on a follower joins the open row.

It can be combined with a [H] to force the panel to become further stacked instead of breaking into its own row. 

    +------+------+
    |..P2..|......|
    +------+......|
    |..P3..|..P1..|
    +------+......|
    |..P4..|......|
    +------+------+

Panel 2
Panel 3
Panel 4 [H][G]

# PAGE 8

Panel 1
Panel 2
Panel 3 [V][L] [END]
[END] (alias [LAST]) anchors the tall panel at the
END of the row. In MANGA the END is the left side,
so P3 sits left and P1/P2 stack right.

    +------+------+
    |......|..P1..|
    |..P3..+------+
    |......|..P2..|
    +------+------+

# PAGE 9
Panel 1 [V]
[V] is a tall panel. Followers fill the other column.

    +------+------+
    |..P2..|......|
    +------+..P1..+
    |..P3..|......|
    +------+------+

Panel 2
Panel 3

# PAGE 10
Panel 1
Panel 2 [WIDE]
[WIDE] is a hero shot, ~15% wider than a normal row.
It bleeds into the page margins. Use sparingly.

    +-----------------+
    |.......P1........|
    +-----------------+
    [.......P2........]
    +-----------------+
    |.......P3........|
    +-----------------+
Panel 3

# PAGE 11
Panel 1 [SPREAD]
[SPREAD] is a splash page that will fill the entire page.

    +-------------+
    |.............|
    |.............|
    |.....P1......|
    |.............|
    |.............|
    +-------------+

# PAGE 12
Panel 1 [H]
[INSET] is a small window inside the panel above it, similar to a close-up, an eye in the corner of a bigger scene.

    +-------------+
    |.............|
    |.....P1......|
    |.+--+........|
    |.|P2|........|
    +--------+--+-+

Panel 2 [INSET]

# PAGE 13
Panel 1 [SPLIT]
[SPLIT] draws a dotted line through the middle of one
panel — top half and bottom half, same outer size.
Good for two quick beats in a single panel.

    +-------------+
    |.....top.....|
    |.:.:.:.:.:.:.|
    |...bottom....|
    +-------------+

# PAGE 14
Panel 1
Dialogue lines go under the panel they belong to. Put the
character name in CAPS on its own line, then the line of
dialogue indented underneath.

    HERO
    The format is plain text. Anyone can read it.

    HERO
    Two short lines beat one long one — Mangaplay sets
    dialogue in Courier Prime, the same monospace screen-
    writers use, so brevity reads faster.

# PAGE 15
Panel 1
Parentheticals sit under the character name to mark tone
or a small action cue.

    HERO
    (whispering)
    Did you hear that?

    HERO
    (thought)
    Mark thought bubbles right in the parenthetical.

# PAGE 16
Panel 1
Sound effects sit on their own line, in caps, with SFX
in front. SFX draws a little larger than dialogue. Keep
each one to a short burst.

    SFX: BOOM

    SFX: CHOMP CHOMP

# PAGE 17 INT. KITCHEN - DAY
Panel 1
A scene heading like INT. KITCHEN - DAY can sit inline on
the page header (above) or stand alone between panels.

INT. CORRIDOR - NIGHT

Panel 2
Standalone scene headings work the same as in Fountain.
Use them to mark a location change inside a single page.

# PAGE 18
Panel 1
Captions and titles sit on their own line.

TITLE Executive Class : Enemy Of The State, | DOROTHY | Age 44

Panel 2
    NARRATION
    Narration uses the same form as dialogue, with NARRATION
    as the speaker. The renderer styles it as a caption box.

# PAGE 19
Panel 1
Transitions are a Fountain primitive — a line ending in
TO: stands alone between panels.

CUT TO:

Panel 2
FADE OUT and FADE IN are also recognised.

FADE OUT.

# PAGE 20
/* PANEL 1 [H] */
For Fountain-safe authoring, panels can also be written
inside Fountain boneyard markers. A pure Fountain reader
will silently strip them; Mangaplay treats them the same
as a regular Panel header.

/* PANEL 2 [INSET] */
The single-line form is the most common.

# PAGE 21
Panel 1
Author notes use double square brackets. They are kept
out of the rendered page, but stay in the source file.

[[ remember to redraw the foreground ]]

Panel 2
Notes are a Fountain primitive — they round-trip through
any Fountain-compatible tool.

# PAGE 22
Panel 1
Inline emphasis works the same as Fountain.

    HERO
    *italic*, **bold**, ***bold italic***, and _underline_.

# PAGE 23
Panel 1
A `>` prefix and `<` suffix on the same line centers it
on the page. A leading `~` marks a lyric line. Both are
Fountain primitives that pass through to the renderer.

> Centered title card <

~ A song line that floats on the page

# PAGE 24
Panel 1
Any valid Fountain screenplay is a valid Mangaplay file.
A `.fountain` file with title page, scene headings, action,
character cues, and transitions parses cleanly — it just
produces a screenplay with no panels until you add them.
